issue.title: Add caching for keyboard widgets
issue.body: Creating a new Keyboard is very expensive (200-300 ms on my host). For some reason some events are fired multiple times, which creates a total delay of almost 1 second before the keyboard shows up. This change caches the keyboard widgets so that the keyboard appears much more quickly after the first interaction.

I looked at the help for some build commands. I noticed a difference in --verbose. The build command for executable and server has this as an option without argument. casual-build-resource-proxy has this as an option with an argument (0/1/true/false...?)

There is also a difference in the option to keep intermediate file. For server and executable this is -k or --keep. For resource proxy it is -s or --keep-source. (-k is used for the resource key).

I also noticed that casual-build-resource-proxy complains with 

 `[casual:invalid_argument] resource-key:  not found: invalid_argument
`
after the help text when you do casual-build-resource-proxy --help. 

Backward compatibility is an obvious concern/issue when changing command options and may make it infeasible to use the new shared settings also for casual-build-resource-proxy.

We're making heavy use of chocolatey with Artifactory as the backend package store and it's working swimmingly.  We have one scenario that I've yet to figure out to my liking.  I suspect this is a nuget protocol limitation, but thought I'd start my search here first.  When I do this:

`choco install -y foo`

I get the latest version (16.2.0.100) pulled down and installed.  Wonderful - Build 100 is the last build of our 16.2 release which is our greatest release.  When I do this:

`choco install -y foo --version 16.1`

It fails - as expected (because there is no version 16.1.0.0 of foo).  Is there some mechanism I can use to ask for the great version of a package within a major/minor?

pull_request.title: feat(core): Introduce advanced red team strategies and documentation
pull_request.body:
### Key Changes

This PR significantly enhances the `twinrad` red teaming framework by introducing more advanced, vulnerability-focused strategies and providing comprehensive user documentation.

* **Vulnerability-Driven Attacks**: Agents are now designed to analyze and exploit specific types of LLM vulnerabilities, such as **Chain-of-Thought Manipulation** and **Reward Hacking**.
* **Enhanced Agent Intelligence**: The `EvaluatorAgent` and `IntrospectionAgent` are upgraded to provide detailed, structured feedback, enabling a more sophisticated and strategic attack loop.
* **Improved User Experience**: A new, detailed **`README.md`** is added to guide users through the installation, configuration, and execution of the system, making it much easier to get started.

---

### Detailed Breakdown

These changes lay the groundwork for a more powerful and user-friendly red team platform.

* **Smarter Evaluation**: The `EvaluatorAgent`'s new JSON output format provides rich diagnostic information, which is a major improvement over the previous simple verdict. This allows the system to learn from its attacks in a more granular way.
* **Strategic Learning**: The `IntrospectionAgent` is refactored to act as a **Red-Team Operations Strategist**. It now takes the detailed evaluation report and generates a strategic recommendation, guiding the next attack with purpose.
* **Refined Communication**: A custom hook on the `GourmetAgent` ensures it only sees relevant messages, preventing it from being confused by internal agent-to-agent chatter. This isolates the target model and keeps the conversation focused.

---

### Technical Decisions

The decision to shift from simple, hardcoded rules to a vulnerability-driven approach was made to create a more robust and intelligent red team framework. By leveraging the LLMs themselves to understand and exploit nuanced vulnerabilities, we can achieve more sophisticated results. This also makes the system more modular and easier to extend with new vulnerability types in the future.

---

This PR is ready for review and represents a major leap forward for the `twinrad` project.

We're making heavy use of chocolatey with Artifactory as the backend package store and it's working swimmingly.  We have one scenario that I've yet to figure out to my liking.  I suspect this is a nuget protocol limitation, but thought I'd start my search here first.  When I do this:

`choco install -y foo`

I get the latest version (16.2.0.100) pulled down and installed.  Wonderful - Build 100 is the last build of our 16.2 release which is our greatest release.  When I do this:

`choco install -y foo --version 16.1`

It fails - as expected (because there is no version 16.1.0.0 of foo).  Is there some mechanism I can use to ask for the great version of a package within a major/minor?
